  <span id="freeText17373895814968253058" style="display:none">"One of the most beautiful love stories ever written."—<i>Paris Match</i><br /><br />Shortly after Albert Cohen left France for London to escape the Nazis, he received news of his mother's death in Marseille. Unable to mourn her, he expressed his grief in a series of moving pieces for <i>La France libre</i>, which later grew into <i>Book of My Mother</i>. Achingly honest, intimate, moving, it is a tribute to all mothers.<br /><br /><b>Albert Cohen</b> (1895–1981) is the author of <i>Solal</i> (1930); <i>Mangeclous</i> (1938); <i>Belle du Seigneur</i> (1968), which was awarded the French Academy's Grand Prix du Roman; and <i>Les Valereux</i> (1969).<br /><br /><br /></span>
