<div id="review_3798790137" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3798790137" />
    <a title="Chris Oleson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/126314906-chris-oleson"><img alt="Chris Oleson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608167807p2/126314906.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3798790137?book_show_action=true">Feb 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris Oleson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris Oleson" href="/user/show/126314906-chris-oleson">Chris Oleson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/126314906-chris-oleson?shelf=translated-literature">translated-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3798790137" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer416726904319296403">This is a disturbing book. Even if the author were compiling such a series of memories of a dead girlfriend or a lover--even of a friend--, I would be left unaffected. However, he is unrelentlessly lamenting the absence of his mother, over and over, with a passion that is worrisome. <br/><br/>I&apos;d hate to witness a battle between Cohen&apos;s mother and Alex Portnoy&apos;s mother. That clash might portend the end of the world.<br/><br/>When my mother died ten years and I couldn&apos;t fly from Japan to America for her funeral, I s</span>
  <span id="freeText416726904319296403" style="display:none">This is a disturbing book. Even if the author were compiling such a series of memories of a dead girlfriend or a lover--even of a friend--, I would be left unaffected. However, he is unrelentlessly lamenting the absence of his mother, over and over, with a passion that is worrisome. <br /><br />I'd hate to witness a battle between Cohen's mother and Alex Portnoy's mother. That clash might portend the end of the world.<br /><br />When my mother died ten years and I couldn't fly from Japan to America for her funeral, I shed no tears; my absence caused no lamentation. Maybe I'm jealous of Cohen's connection and love for his mother. I'll cop to that.<br /><br />Cohen is an impressive lyrical writer. Such intensity for a parent is deeply troubling. Deeply.</span>
  <a data-text-id="416726904319296403" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


