<span id="freeTextContainer6993719628862856912">On the one hand, there are some beautiful passages about childhood and motherhood. On the other, sometimes his moaning about death is insufferable (although appropriate, I suppose, since on some level he wishes he could be that whiny kid again). And then there are the horribly patronizing descriptions of his mother... he loves her and acknowledges that no son ever realizes his mother is a human being of her own accord, and then he spends the entire book painting her as an infantile creature whos</span>
  <span id="freeText6993719628862856912" style="display:none">On the one hand, there are some beautiful passages about childhood and motherhood. On the other, sometimes his moaning about death is insufferable (although appropriate, I suppose, since on some level he wishes he could be that whiny kid again). And then there are the horribly patronizing descriptions of his mother... he loves her and acknowledges that no son ever realizes his mother is a human being of her own accord, and then he spends the entire book painting her as an infantile creature whose only purpose in life was to serve him. I struggled with that. </span>
