    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3488505790" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3488505790" />
    <a title="Hal" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2622717-hal"><img alt="Hal" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1584285040p2/2622717.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3488505790?book_show_action=true">Aug 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hal" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hal" href="/user/show/2622717-hal">Hal</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9782070393565" href="/book/show/435591.Le_Livre_de_ma_m_re">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3488505790" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15025579912092627425">A few good bits where the author recounts memories of time he&apos;s spent with his mother, going to cafés or her visiting him in Genva when he&apos;s older, or his mother waiting for him and his father with dinner on Sabath. Unfortunately, most of the book is filled with very repetitive laments around grief and losing someone. His father is conspicuously and almost entirely absent throughout. I would have liked to read more episodes taken from his life and fewer lyrical musings about life and death.</span>
  <span id="freeText15025579912092627425" style="display:none">A few good bits where the author recounts memories of time he's spent with his mother, going to cafés or her visiting him in Genva when he's older, or his mother waiting for him and his father with dinner on Sabath. Unfortunately, most of the book is filled with very repetitive laments around grief and losing someone. His father is conspicuously and almost entirely absent throughout. I would have liked to read more episodes taken from his life and fewer lyrical musings about life and death.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15025579912092627425" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


